{"/service/ndnp/mdu/batch_mdu_jackinthepulpit_ver01/data/sn83016209/00383342156/1949063001/0353.xml":{"full_text":"Thursday, June 30, 1949.\nSEALED BIDS\nSealed bids will be received by\nthe Purchasing Bureau, Court\nHouse, Rockville, Md., on July 15,\n1949, at 11:00 A. M. for furnish\ning Montgomery County with gar\nbage and refuse disposal service.\nFurther specifications may be ob\ntAied from the Purchasing Bu\nreau.\nI. G. McNAYR,\n363 Purchasing Agent.\nOrder Nisi\u2014\nIN THE CIRCUIT COURT FOR\nMONTGOMERY COUNTY,\nAS A COURT OF EQUITY.\nNo. 13,616 Equity.\nCharles V. Imlay, Plaintiff,\nvs.\nEletta Money, William Money, et\nal,\nDefendants.\nORDERED, this 27th day of\nJune A. D. 1949, by the Circuit\nCourt for Montgomery County, as\na Court of Equity, that the sale\nmade by Donald A. DeLashmutt,\nTrustee, to Brooke B. Jackson, and\nreported in the above entitled\ncause, be ratified and confirmed,\nunless cause to the contrary there\nof be shown on or before the 25th\nday of July next: Provided a copy\nof this order be inserted in some\nnewspaper published in said Mont\ngomery county, once in each of\nthree successive weeks before the\nsaid 25th day of July, 1949.\nThe report states the amount of\nthe sale to be $2,500.00.\nCLAYTON K. WATKINS,\nClerk of the Circuit Court for\nMontgomery County.\nTrue Copy\u2014Test:\nCLAYTON K. WATKINS,\nClerk. 361\nNisi\u2014\nk IN THE CIRCUIT COURT FOR\nMONTGOMERY COUNTY,\ni AS A COURT OF EQUITY.\nNo. 14080 Equity.\nIn the matter of the Mortgage\nfrom George Raymond Smith\nand Ruth Elizabeth Smith,\nto\nThe Bank of Damascus.\nORDERED, this 27th day of\nJune A. D. 1949, by the Circuit\nCourt for Montgomery County, as\na Court of Equity, that the sale\nmade by Donald A. DeLashmutt,\nperson named in Mortgage to\nmake sale, to The Bank of Damas\ncus, Damascus, Maryland, and re\nported in the above entitled cause,\nbe ratified and confirmed, unless\ncause to the contrary thereof be\nshown on or before the 25th day of\nJuly next: Provided a copy of this\norder be inserted in some news\npaper- published in said Montgom\n<ery county, once in each of three\nsuccessive weeks before the said\n25th day of July, 1949.\nThe report states the amount of\nthe sale to be $5,900.00.\nCLAYTON K. WATKINS,\n9 Clerk of the Circuit Court for\nMontgomery County.\nTrue Copy\u2014Test: x\nCLAYTON K. WATKINS,\nClerk. 362\nOrder Nisi\u2014\nIN THE CIRCUIT COURT FOR\nMONTGOMERY COUNTY,\nAS A COURT OF EQUITY.\nNo. 14121 Equity.\nIn the Matter of the Deed of Trust\nfrom Tekton Construction Com\npany, Inc., a Delaware Corpora\ntion\nto\nMartin R. West, Earl M. Mackin\ntosh, and Edward K. Jones,\nTrustees.\nORDERED, this 27th day of\nJune A. D. 1949, by the Circuit\n\u25a0Jfe \u00aeWrt for Montgomery County, as\nsTCourt of Equity, that the sale\nmade by Martin R. West, Earl M.\nMackintosh and Edward K. Jones,\nTrustees, to John D. Bowman, Jr.,\nand Nancy D. Bowman, his wife,\nand reported in the above entitled\ncause, be ratified and confirmed,\nunless cause to the contrary there\nof be shown on or before the 25th\nk day of July next: Provided a copy\nof this order be inserted in some\nnewspaper published in said Mont\ngomery county, once in each of\nthree successive weeks before the\nsaid 25th day of July, 1949.\nThe report states the amount of\nJB the sale to be $10,100.00.\nI CLAYTON K. WATKINS,\nl Clerk of the Circuit Court for\nMontgomery County.\nM True Copy\u2014Test:\nCLAYTON K. WATKINS,\nIf' Clerk. 360\nPoplar Heights Livestock Sale\n2 miles west of Lisbon\n3 miles east of Ridgeville on Route 40\nTHURSDAY, JULY 7, 1949 ll A.M.\nIV',\nCattle, calves, hogs, horses, poultry, farm machin\nery, new lumber, Locust posts, 50 head cattle, includ\ning 20 fresh cows and close springers. 5 bulls, 25 head\nof heifers, 6 months to 2 years old. Several will\nfreshen in fall. 50 pigs and shoats, 5 brood sows.\nFarm machinery of all kinds; mowers, rakes, plows,\nharrows, wagons, drills.\nIf you have anything to sell bring it in. Com\nmission reasonable.\nC. VERNON RHODERICK,\nMt. Airy 143-J-4.\nJohn Null and Edgar Warfield, Auctioneers.\nAlvie Etzler and Calvin Murray, Clerks.\nLiquor Control Board\nfor Montgomery County\nNOTICE\nApplication having been made\nto The Liquor Contrdl Board for\nMontgomery County for approval\nof license to sell Alcoholic Bev\nerages pursuant to the provisions\nof Article 2B of the Annotated\nCode of Maryland, as amended,\nnotice is hereby given that the\nsaid application is made by:\nHarold C. Ale, William T.\nGreenville, and Morton T. Iler,\nfor and on behalf of Montgomery\nCounty Post No. 2958, Veterans\nof Foreign Wars of the United\nStates, Inc., for a Class \u201cD\u201d, On\nSale Generally Beer and Light\nWine License for the V.F.W.\nHome, Halpine, Rockville Pike,\nRockville, Maryland.\nPursuant to law the Board has\nfixed\nTHURSDAY, JULY 21, 1949\nat 10:00 A.M.\nin the Hearing Room of the Dis\npensary Building, Silver Spring,\nMaryland, for hearing on said\napplication which is on file in the\noffice of The Liquor Control\nBoard, Silver Spring, Maryland.\nAny person desiring to be heard\nin favor of or in opposition to\nthe approval of said application\nshould appear at time and\nplace fixed for said hearing.\nLIQUOR CONTROL BOARD FOR\nMONTGOMERY COUNTY\nBy: J. FOREST WALKER,\nChairman.\nPLUMMER M. SHEARIN,\nSecretary. 350\nState of Maryland\nSTATE ROADS COMMISSION\nNOTICE TO CONTRACTORS\nState Roads Project\nSEALED PROPOSALS for the\nimprovement of one (1) section\nof highway, as follows:\nMONTGOMERY COUNTY CON\nTRACT NO. M-460-315\nThis project includes the fur\nnishing, delivering, and apply\ning of Bituminous Concrete Re\nsurfacing, Specification \u2018B\u2019,\nalong two (2) sections of high\nway, as follows:\n1. Along Bradley Boulevard,\nState Route No. 191, beginning\nat Wisconsin Avenue and ex\ntending Southerly to Leland\nStreet, for a distance of 0.369\nmile.\n2. Along Leland Street, State\nRoute No. 82, beginning at\nBradley Lane and extending\nNortherly to the East-West\nHighway for a distance of\n1.102 miles\u2014A total distance\nof 1.471 miles.\nThe employment agency for\nfurnishing labor on the above\nproject is MARYLAND STATE\nEMPLOYMENT SERVICE,\n8511 COLESVILLE RD., SIL\nVER SPRING, MD.\nwill be received by the State\nRoads Commission at its offices,\n108 East Lexington Street, Balti\nmore, Maryland, until 12 Noon,\nDaylight Saving Time, on the 12th\nday of July, 1949, at which time\nand place they will be publicly\nopened and read. QUALIFICA\nTION OF BIDDERS REQUIRED.\nBids must be made upon the\nblank proposal form which, with\nspecifications and plans will be\nfurnished by the Commission upon\napplication and cash payment of\n$5.00, for each separate project,\nas hereafter no charges will be\npermitted.\nNo bids will be received unless\naccompanied by a certified check\nor bid bond payable to the State\nRoads Commission of Maryland,\nas required by Chapter 58\u2018 Acts\nof 1943, of the amount as set\nforth in the proposal form.\nThe sudbessful bidder will be\nrequired to give bond, and comply\nwith the Acts of the General As\nsembly of Maryland, respecting\ncontracts. NO REFUND WILL\nBE MADE FOR RETURN OF\nSPECIFICATIONS AND PLANS.\nThe Commission reserves the\nright to reject any and all bids.\nBY ORDER of the State Roads\nCommission this 28th day of June,\n1949.\nROBERT M. REINDOLLAR,\nChairman.\nL. H. STEUART, Secretary.\n365\nSEALED BIDS\nSealed bids will be received by\nthe Purchasing Bureau, Court\nHouse, Rockville, Md., on July 15,\n1949, at 2:00 P. M. for furnishing\nMontgomery County with Tires\nand Tubes. Further specifications\nmay be obtained from the Purchas\ning Bureau.\nI. G. McNAYR,\n364 Purchasing Agent.\nOfficials Plan\nSafety Vigil\nOver Holiday\nColonel Beverly Ober, Baltimore\nPolice Commissioner, Colonel\nCarey Jarman, Superintendent of\nthe Maryland State Police, Robert\nM. Reindollar, Chairman State\nRoads Commission, and William H.\nBishop, Jr., Director of the Mary\nland Traffic Safety Commission,\nplan a special safety vigil for the\nlong July 4th holiday.\nHaving established one of the\nfinest safety records in the U. S.\nduring the 1948 July 4th weekend,\nMaryland\u2019s guardians of highway\nsafety will be out in full force.\nAll leaves, furloughs and vaca\ntions for all traffic enforcement\nofficers on Maryland highways are\ncancelled to put the full weight of\ntraffic assistance at disposal of\nmotorists who will be traveling\nMaryland highways over the long\nweek-end.\nAccording to Maryland\u2019s Bureau\non Traffic Statistics, pedestrian\ncasualties still head the list. Special\ncaution and warning is directed to\npedestrians who cross roads where\nthere is no intersection or no traffic\nsignal.\nCrossing against the signal,\nwalking in roadways, stepping\nfrom behind parked cars or lying\nin the roadway while making tire\nrepairs also stand high on the list\nof accident causes.\nFor the period July 2 to July 5,\ninclusive, last year, there were\neleven accidents on Howard County\nroads. Eight were reported on\nRoute 1, one each on routes 32 and\n175 and one on an unnumbered\nroad. Although there were no\nfatalities, one person was injured\nin an accident on Washington\nboulevard during the day and\nthirty-five were injured in four\naccidents on the same road at\nnight.\nBusiness Outlook\nAccording to some experts, the\ncurrent business decline is about\nhalf over, and by fall, an upturn\nin business is expected. The output\nof goods is down by about 10 per\ncent and wholesale prices are down\n8 per cent. Consumer buying is\nholding up fairly well, while busi\nness buyers are holding up, wait\ning for prices to decline further.\nThe sackbut was an early form\nof trombone, according to the En\ncyclopaedia Britannica.\nUnemployment\nThe trend toward unemployment\nis continuing, with an estimated\n4,000,000 persons now out of work\nand seeking jobs. Industry, as a\nwhole, is tightening upon workers\nand a large number who are still\non the job are having their hours\ncurtailed. Even so, more than 59,-\n000,000 persons are on the nation\u2019s\npayrolls, 9,C00,000 more than in\nprewar 1940.\nWisdom comes to individuals in\nbroken doses and few human\nbeings have much of it.\nUnemployment rise held no in\ndication of recession now.\naave Your Fireworks and Eat Them Too\nmM. T\n\u25a0\u25a0pH 4 \u201ci\u00dfr a\nJsFa\u00dfw JMm m\nSnow in winter and sun in sum- band uses sieved hard cooked egg\nmer usually spell playtime for week white mixed with softened cream\nends. Since Fourth of July falls on cheese, horseradish, and chives\nST St, \"TS S\u201c;, llul\nfor Mom unless the family plans to J\n\u2022'eat out.\" Third band Is made of chopped\nChances are that at least one pic- ed b e H held t ether wlth\nnic supper will be held in the back- u ?f\u201c\u201c on of ,aU base. Soften\nyard, on the terrace, or under cover :_ teaspo plaln gelatln ,n 1 table\nshould the day be wet or chilly. p co 1 w water Heat 2 table-\nHow does this menu sound for ?P\u00b0\u00b0 n v ne Kar with 1 tablespoon\nsuch a supper, served buffet style? J\u201c lce 4 whn boiling P\u00b0ur It\nFlrJ..rk. FI-., \u00b0Y* r th softened gelatin. Stir t\nireworks Fiesta Food dissolve the gelaUn. Add beets Chill\nTomato Juice cocktail until rather firm, then use as the\nFirecracker rolls outside or third band of color\nPlnwheel pie Potato chips Remove a slice from a peeled\nq rlUed Hamburgers hard-cooked egg. Take out the yolk.\nRadish Torpedoes SL c Fill the opening with washed, perky\nWatermelon Coffee parsley. Set the egg cup In a hole\nHere are recipes and helps. made at center of top bread slice.\nTomato Juice Cocktail Put slices of stuffed olives on\nChill well flavored tomato juice band Cut narrow strips of\nPour some of It Into the Ice cube radiate\ntrav At *frvinff time add a cube raa ale tnese from the center\na. lu To a H\u20acnS?,\u201e of .TT \u2018plT\nthtTmore \u00a3?V\u00a3?\ngenerously. Spread with mustard v\u2122 or th I better\n\u201ens At serving Bmall and a mild explosive\n.tend,, wip ol plmtento !u*.\nPlnwheel Pie a bang. Round radishes may be\nBuy the largest round loaf of rye called today s torpedoes,\nbread you can find. Cut off the bot- When fireworks are to be set off,\ntom crust. Cut two round slices, the fuses are lighted by applying a\nabout Vk Inch thick. Remove crusts, slender stick of a slow burning ms-\nButter each slice Spread a thick terial which used to be called\nlayer of deviled ham on the bot- \"punk.\u2019' The carrot sticks can be\ntom slice. Top with second slice of of the same size, but not the un\n\u2022iread. Spread three bands of col- attractive gray brown color which\nwful food on the top slice First used to Identify punk\nMONTGOMERY COUNTY SENTINEL, ROCKVILLE, Mil.\nComptroller Warns All\nDelinquent Taxpayers\nShopkeepers, tavernkeepers and\nall other retail merchants who\nhave been licensed by the State of\nMaryland for the collection of\nsales taxes are warned today by\nJames J. Lacy, State\nthat the probationary period is\nover and that all who are delin\nquent turning in to the State taxes\ncollected will be prosecuted under\neither, or both, civil and criminal\nlaws.\n\u201cOf course,\u201d Lacy continued,\n\u201cthe Comptroller\u2019s office is aware\nof the many difficulties facing\nmost businessmen at this time and\nthere is no thought of personal\nharassment intended in this drive\nfor enforcement of the iSales Tax.\nBut, by far, the greater majority\nof the retail trade in the State is\ncooperating wholeheartedly in the\nprogram and there is no reason\nwhy the remaining few should be\ndelinquent in making their re\nturns. My office is merely perform\ning its sworn duty to enforcing a\nlaw passed by the legislature. And\nif everyone carries out his part\nunder this law the entire tax bur\nden will be materially lightened.\nThis not only applies to the Sales\nTax but to the Income Tax as\nwell.\u201d\nNow that the Sales Tax law has\nbeen in force for two years, Lacy\nadded, the Sales Tax Division of\nhis office is able to tell exactly\nwhich of the 67,060 licensees has\nfailed to file and pay their current\nmonthly Sales Tax return. But,\nbefore court action is instituted,\nLacy said, every effort is made to\nnotify the delinquent licensee by\nmail that the taxes collected, and\ndue the State, have not been paid.\nThis notice is usually sufficient\nwarning, continued Lacy, for most\nof the tardy licensees. However,\nthere still remains the recalcitrant\nfew who must again be warned\nthat they now not only owe the\nState the taxes due but face a pen\nalty up of 100 per cent plus inter\nest at the rate of 1 per cent per\nmonth.\nIf this warning is ignored, the\nenforcement department takes\nover. Inspectors are sent to the\nestablishment and the books are\naudited. The delinquent licensee is\nthen shown the findings and if he\nstill demurs, either civil or crimi\nnal, or both, actions are then in\nstituted and the matter is brought\nbefore the courts.\nHowever, Lacy pointed out, it is\nnot mandatory under the sales tax\nlaw that the delinquent be notified\nthrough the mails before any legal\naction may be started by the en\nforcement division.\nUntil now, Mr. Lacy empha\nsized, a concentrated effort to col\nlect the delinquent taxes due the\nState has been confined to Balti\nmore City, due to lack of man\npower in the enforcement depart\nment but in the past seven months\nin this area the number of delin\nquent accounts have been cut more\nthan sixty per cent. For the month\nof August, last year, 4,702 licen\nsees failed to file and pay their\nmonthly returns, but by March of\nthis year, the number had been re\nduced to 1,870.\nSeveral hundred of these cases\nhave been processed in the past\nthree weeks and resulted in the\ncollection of taxes, penalties and\ninterest of more than $40,000.\nSince the inception of the Sales\nTax law over $626,000 has been\ncollected as the result of investiga\ntive activity.\nAnd in the cases brought before\nthe courts by the enforcement di\nvision, 17 convictions were ob\ntained in Baltimore City and 20 in\nthe counties. In addition to collect\ning the taxes due, the state was\nenriched by a total $10,072 from\nfines imposed. Also two delinquents\nserved 30-day jail sentences and\n16 sentences were suspended.\nPleased with the success of the\nenforcement division in the collec\ntion of overdue sales taxes in Bal\ntimore City, Mr. Lacy pointed out\nthat a staff of investigators, head\ned by the chief, J. Joseph McDer\nmott, has begun a county by coun\nty campaign throughout the State.\nIn this concerted drive, the fly\ning squad is armed with names\nand addresses of nearly 2,500 busi\nnesses that are in arrears in sales\ntaxes owed the State.\nBeats Girl, 4, With Stick\nYakima, Wash. Because his\nlittle four year -old daughter\nwouldn\u2019t eat, Walter Minion, 41,\ntold police he had beaten the child\nwith a stick of wood 2 inches\nthick. She was taken to a hospital\nwith her skull and jaw fractured.\nResearchers Making Progress In\nPolio Study; Give Hints For Parents\nWhen infantile paralysis strikes\nanywhere in the United States,\ndoctors and scientists move in at\nonce to track down sources of\ninfection and protect the commun\nity. These polio detectives have\ndiscovered important facts about\nthe transmission of the virus by\nflies, human contact, and faulty\nplumbing, says Alan Hynd, Writ\ning in Redbook Magazine for July,\nhe gives five precautions that you\nand your family can take against\nthis dread disease:\n\u201cThe National Foundation for\nInfantile Paralysis, which finan\nces the investigations of epidemi\nologists, or polio detectives, has\nscientific grounds for warning\nmothers each year at this time to\nsec that their childen do not get\nchilled or fatigued. Bodily de\nfenses against any disease are\nlowered by exhaustion; thus a\nrested body, or a body whose\nfunctions are not disturbed by the\nshock inherent in chilling, could\nvery well be the difference be\ntween a severe and a mild attack\nof polio, or a mild attack and no\nattack at all.\n\u201cThe greatest undertaking now\nis a nation-wide laboratory quest,\nfinanced by the March of Dimes,\nfor a poliomyelitis vaccine ad\nmittedly several years away at\nthe very nearest. In the meantime\nI our main hope centers around\ntreatment and the smashing of the\nchains of transmission by which\nthe virus spreads.\n\u201cThe common house fly does not\nseem to be such a frequent car\nrier of the polio virus as the green\nbottle fiy or the blue bottle fly.\ni Whether a fly brings the virus\ninto a locality and starts an epi\ndemic, or whether it contacts the\nvirus during an epidemic has long\nbaffled polio sleuths. Also unan\nswerable so far is the question of\nwhether the fly accounts for an\nappreciable amount of polio trans\nmission.\n\u201cThe fly is apparently the only\ninhabitant of the insect world that\ncarries the polio virus. This is\nprobably due to its habit of feed\ning off human waste matter, which\nin itself is known to be the great\nest source of habitation of the\npolio virus aside from the human\nbody itself.\n\u201cEpidemiologists have proved\nthat faculty plumbing can be a\ndangerous link in the chain of\nvirus transmission. Milk has never\nbeen found to contain polio virus\nsecreted by a cow, but single\nbatches can be infected otherwise.\nPolio detectives are thought to\nmiss the evidence because the dis\nease is not reported for three days\nto thirty-five days after it appears;\nit takes that long for the virus\nto fell a victim after entering the\nsystem. The virus itself is known\nto be highly susceptible to tem\nperature changes and other fac\ntors when it is not inhabiting a\nliving cell. Thus it is possible that\non one day it may be virulent in\na food or drink supply, or in dust\nor the air, and be completely ab\nsent the next.\n\u201cThe greatest family tragedy in\nthe history, of poliomyelitis struck\nin a home In Akron, Ohio, in\nAugust, 1941. Within the space of\ntwenty-four hours, five of the six\nchildren came down with bulbar\npolio, the most dreaded form of\nthe disease. Forty-eight hours\nlater, three of them were dead,\nand two hopelessly crippled. Only\nthe youngest, a two-and-a-half\nyear old boy, escaped the ravages\nof the disease.\n\u201cApparently two of the chil\ndren had picked up the polio virus\nwhile* visiting a cousin. Eleven\ndays before they were stricken,\nthp children had had their tonsils\nremoved\u2014all except the child who\n1949 Maryland\nHighway Map\nNow Available\nMaryland\u2019s Official 1949 High\nway Map made its first appearance\ntoday.\nPrepared by the State Roads\nCommission, the map provides the\nusual inventory of highways\nthroughout Maryland, showing\nmajor routes in red, secondary\nroads by solid black lines, with\nother designations for less heavily\ntraveled arteries. Distances be\ntween principal points are shown\nin red figures.\nA feature which endeared the\n1948 Maryland Highway Map to\nmotorists an accordian fold,\nwhich permits study of any section\nof the map without unfolding it to\nits full length has been retained\nin the 1949 edition.\nThe location and telephone num\nbers of the various State Police\nSubstations have been added to\nthe data on the 1949 map.\nThe entire map is divided into\nnumbered squares, permitting the\nquick location of any city, town or\nvillage by reference to a key list\nprinted at the edge of the map.\nThe only changes in the pictorial\ndisplay on the reverse side of, the\nmap is a substitution of the Ham\nmond-Harwood House for a rustic\nscene near Hancock, and the re\nplacement of two pictures one\nof a Chesapeake Bay ferry, the\nother of a boat load of shad \u2014by\nan artist's drawing of the Chesa\npeake Bay Bridge.\nA section devoted to Maryland\u2019s\ntraffic laws includes an illustration\nof the now-official signal for a\nhad not come down with polio.\nAlthough field sleuths had, before\nthe Akron tragedy, been suspi\ncious of a connection between bul\nbar (brain) polio and tonsillec\ntomies, adenoid operations and\ntooth extractions, it was not until\nthe family tragedy that the Na\ntional Foundation went on record\nunequivocally as warning against\nsuch operations during the polio\nseason, unless such operations are\nurgent.\n\u201cDirect contact between a child\nwho is about to come down with\npolio and one who has not been\ninfected has also been found to\nbe one of the strongest links in\nthe chain of transmission.\n\u201cHere are five precautions\nagainst polio:\n\u201c1. Avoid crowds and places\nwhere close contact with other\npersons is likely.\n\u201c2. Avoid over-fatigue caused\nby too-active play or exercise, or\nby irregular hours.\n\u201c3. Avoid swimming in polluted\nwater. Use only beaches or public\npools declared safe by local health\nauthorities.\n\"4. Avoid sudden chilling. Re\nmove wet shoes and clothing at\nonce and keep extra blankets and\nheavier clothing handy for sud\nden weather changes.\n\u201c5. Observe the golden rule of\npersonal cleanliness. Keep food\ntightly covered and safe from flies\nor other insects. Garbage should\nbo tightly covered and, if other\ndisposal facilities are lacking, it\nshould be buried or burned.\n\u201cThese are some polio symptoms:\nheadache, nausea or upset stomach,\nsnuscle soreness or stiffness, and\nunexplained fever. Should polio\nstrike in your family, call a doctor\nimmediately. Early diagnosis and\nprompt treatment by qualified med\nical personnel often prevent serious\ncrippling, the National Foundation\nhas pointed out.\n\u201cIf polio is actually diagnosed,\ncontact the chapter of the National\nFoundation for Infantile Paralysis\nserving your community. The\nchapter will pay that part of the\ncost of care and treatment which\npatient or family cannot meet.\u201d\n||Q\nMxrfcet Your WtuM tad Hartoy\nThroath Southern Slates Grain Make!-\nStrvict...tnd pt lop prices!\nQUOTATIONS bo*d on notional\nmorkoti and official grodo*. toro min\nimum handling margin and low ovar\nhad aiivrt you a high#* grlco. fully\nmetwr* groin* (top qvolity) bring top\npricot through Southern Stole* Groin\nMarketing Service!\nFor\nPrice Quotations\nCall\nGaithersburg 91\nSouthern. States\nwyUjvi Gaithersburg\n\\\u00a7gj!7 Servite\nGaithersburg, Md.\nSuit-Dress For Travel, Formal\nWear Leads Summer Fashion News\nFor summer travel and formal\nwear there is nothing so appro\npriate as a suit-dress. It has all\nthe tailored smartness of a suit\nand the coolness of a dress, says\nMarian Corey. Writing in McCall\u2019s\nfor July, she tells you the best\ncolors and fabrics for this incom\nparable costume and describes\nsome fall and college clothes:\n\u201cYou are about to step off some\nwhere by plane, train or car, and\nthe old old question rears its horrid\nhead\u2014what to wear? Definitely\nyour wool suit will be too hot. And\nyour summer dresses too informal.\nWhat you need is something that\nwill go naturally with hat, bag and\ngloves. Something that is tailored\nand formal for daytime. Something\nthat will stay reasonably fresh a\nlong time. Something like a suit,\nbut cooler. In other words, you need\na suit-dress.\n\u201cSuit-uresses have the suit look,\nwhich is right for travel. They are\ncooler than suits, being made of\nthinner materials and unlincd.\nBlouses are not needed. And, final\nly, if you make your own, you will\ndiscover that it is much simpler\nto make a suit-dress than a suit.\n\u201cFor travelling and general run\nning around, the best colors for\nthis incomparable costume are the\ndark ones. The best fabrics are\nfour heavy crepe, shantung,\nheavy sheer, and faille.\n\u201cA heavy sheer is very right for\none good-looking suit-dress, be\nright turn the driver\u2019s arm\nbeing extended upward.\nAs in previous years, the maps\nwill be distributed through the\nState Police, Chambers of Com\nmerce in the several cities, 